%N A342222 a(n) is the smallest m such that a regular m-gon with all diagonals drawn contains a cell with n sides, or a(n) = -1 if no such m exists.
%C A342222 Theorem: If n is odd then a(n) = n.
%C A342222 Proof. (i) If n is odd then the central cell in a regular n-gon with all diagonals drawn is a smaller regular n-gon. So if n is odd, then a(n) <= n.
%C A342222 (ii) Suppose a convex m-gon, not necessarily regular, with all diagonals drawn has a cell with e edges. Each edge when extended meets two vertices, so at most 2e vertices are involved in defining the boundary of that cell.
%C A342222 On the other hand no vertex can define more than two edges of the cell, so 2e <= 2m, so e <= m. So to get an n-sided cell, we need at least n vertices. So a(n) >= n. QED.
%C A342222 If a(20) > 0 it is greater than 765 - _Scott R. Shannon_, Nov 30 2021
